The Lunar Lander Environment¶

Lunar Lander is a popular reinforcement learning (RL) environment where an agent must control a lunar lander ship to land safely on the moon's surface. The goal of the agent is to maximize the total reward obtained by landing the lander in a landing area while avoiding obstacles.

In this environment, the state of the environment includes variables like the position, velocity, and angle of the lunar lander. The agent must choose one of several possible actions at each time step, such as increasing or decreasing the thrust in one of the engines. The agent receives a reward based on the state of the lander and the chosen action, with larger rewards for landing safely and smaller rewards (or penalties) for crashing or using too much fuel.

The Lunar Lander environment is a challenging problem for reinforcement learning algorithms, as it requires balancing multiple objectives and trade-offs, such as controlling the speed and trajectory of the lander, conserving fuel, and avoiding obstacles. This makes it a popular benchmark environment for testing and comparing different RL algorithms.

State Variables: 8 total

  • x-coordinates
  • y-coordinates
  • x-velocity
  • y-velocity
  • angle of ship
  • angular velocity (rate of turning)
  • left-touch (whether left leg in contact with ground)
  • right-touch (whether right leg in contact with ground)

Action Space: 4 total

  • Do nothing
  • Fire left engine
  • Fire main engine
  • Fire right engine

def test_already_trained_model(trained_model,episodes=10,render=True):
    rewards_list = []
    num_test_episode = episodes
    env = gym.make("LunarLander-v2")
    print("Starting Testing of the trained model...")

    step_count = 1000

    for test_episode in range(num_test_episode):
        current_state = env.reset()
        num_observation_space = env.observation_space.shape[0]
        current_state = np.reshape(current_state, [1, num_observation_space])
        reward_for_episode = 0
        for step in range(step_count):
            if render:
              env.render()
            selected_action = np.argmax(trained_model.predict(current_state)[0])
            new_state, reward, done, info = env.step(selected_action)
            new_state = np.reshape(new_state, [1, num_observation_space])
            current_state = new_state
            reward_for_episode += reward
            if done:
                break
        rewards_list.append(reward_for_episode)
        print(test_episode, "\t: Episode || Reward: ", reward_for_episode)

    return rewards_list


def plot_df(df, chart_name, title, x_axis_label, y_axis_label):
    plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 17})
    df['rolling_mean'] = df[df.columns[0]].rolling(100).mean()
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
    plt.close()
    plt.figure()
    # plot = df.plot(linewidth=1.5, figsize=(15, 8), title=title)
    plot = df.plot(linewidth=1.5, figsize=(15, 8))
    plot.set_xlabel(x_axis_label)
    plot.set_ylabel(y_axis_label)
    # plt.ylim((-400, 300))
    fig = plot.get_figure()
    plt.legend().set_visible(False)
    fig.savefig(save_dir+f'/{chart_name}')


def plot_df2(df, chart_name, title, x_axis_label, y_axis_label):
    df['mean'] = df[df.columns[0]].mean()
    plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 17})
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
    plt.close()
    plt.figure()
    # plot = df.plot(linewidth=1.5, figsize=(15, 8), title=title)
    plot = df.plot(linewidth=1.5, figsize=(15, 8))
    plot.set_xlabel(x_axis_label)
    plot.set_ylabel(y_axis_label)
    plt.ylim((0, 300))
    plt.xlim((0, 100))
    plt.legend().set_visible(False)
    fig = plot.get_figure()
    fig.savefig(save_dir+f'/{chart_name}')


def plot_experiments(df, chart_name, title, x_axis_label, y_axis_label, y_limit):
    plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 17})
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
    plt.close()
    plt.figure()
    plot = df.plot(linewidth=1, figsize=(15, 8), title=title)
    plot.set_xlabel(x_axis_label)
    plot.set_ylabel(y_axis_label)
    plt.ylim(y_limit)
    fig = plot.get_figure()
    fig.savefig(save_dir+f'/{chart_name}')
    

def run_experiment_for_gamma():
    print('Running Experiment for gamma...')
    env = gym.make('LunarLander-v2')

    # set seeds
    env.seed(21)
    np.random.seed(21)

    # setting up params
    lr = 0.001
    epsilon = 1.0
    epsilon_decay = 0.995
    gamma_list = [0.99, 0.9, 0.8, 0.7]
    training_episodes = 1000

    rewards_list_for_gammas = []
    for gamma_value in gamma_list:
        model = DQN(env, lr, gamma_value, epsilon, epsilon_decay)
        print("Training model for Gamma: {}".format(gamma_value))
        model.train(training_episodes, False)
        rewards_list_for_gammas.append(model.rewards_list)

    pickle.dump(rewards_list_for_gammas, open("rewards_list_for_gammas.p", "wb"))
    rewards_list_for_gammas = pickle.load(open("rewards_list_for_gammas.p", "rb"))

    gamma_rewards_pd = pd.DataFrame(index=pd.Series(range(1, training_episodes + 1)))
    for i in range(len(gamma_list)):
        col_name = "gamma=" + str(gamma_list[i])
        gamma_rewards_pd[col_name] = rewards_list_for_gammas[i]
    plot_experiments(gamma_rewards_pd, "Figure 4: Rewards per episode for different gamma values",
                     "Figure 4: Rewards per episode for different gamma values", "Episodes", "Reward", (-600, 300))


def run_experiment_for_lr():
    print('Running Experiment for learning rate...')
    env = gym.make('LunarLander-v2')

    # set seeds
    env.seed(21)
    np.random.seed(21)

    # setting up params
    lr_values = [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1]
    epsilon = 1.0
    epsilon_decay = 0.995
    gamma = 0.99
    training_episodes = 1000
    rewards_list_for_lrs = []
    for lr_value in lr_values:
        model = DQN(env, lr_value, gamma, epsilon, epsilon_decay)
        print("Training model for LR: {}".format(lr_value))
        model.train(training_episodes, False)
        rewards_list_for_lrs.append(model.rewards_list)

    pickle.dump(rewards_list_for_lrs, open("rewards_list_for_lrs.p", "wb"))
    rewards_list_for_lrs = pickle.load(open("rewards_list_for_lrs.p", "rb"))

    lr_rewards_pd = pd.DataFrame(index=pd.Series(range(1, training_episodes + 1)))
    for i in range(len(lr_values)):
        col_name = "lr="+ str(lr_values[i])
        lr_rewards_pd[col_name] = rewards_list_for_lrs[i]
    plot_experiments(lr_rewards_pd, "Figure 3: Rewards per episode for different learning rates", "Figure 3: Rewards per episode for different learning rates", "Episodes", "Reward", (-2000, 300))


def run_experiment_for_ed():
    print('Running Experiment for epsilon decay...')
    env = gym.make('LunarLander-v2')

    # set seeds
    env.seed(21)
    np.random.seed(21)

    # setting up params
    lr = 0.001
    epsilon = 1.0
    ed_values = [0.999, 0.995, 0.990, 0.9]
    gamma = 0.99
    training_episodes = 1000

    rewards_list_for_ed = []
    for ed in ed_values:
        save_dir = "hp_ed_"+ str(ed) + "_"
        model = DQN(env, lr, gamma, epsilon, ed)
        print("Training model for ED: {}".format(ed))
        model.train(training_episodes, False)
        rewards_list_for_ed.append(model.rewards_list)

    pickle.dump(rewards_list_for_ed, open("rewards_list_for_ed.p", "wb"))
    rewards_list_for_ed = pickle.load(open("rewards_list_for_ed.p", "rb"))

    ed_rewards_pd = pd.DataFrame(index=pd.Series(range(1, training_episodes+1)))
    for i in range(len(ed_values)):
        col_name = "epsilon_decay = "+ str(ed_values[i])
        ed_rewards_pd[col_name] = rewards_list_for_ed[i]
    plot_experiments(ed_rewards_pd, "Figure 5: Rewards per episode for different epsilon() decay", "Figure 5: Rewards per episode for different epsilon() decay values", "Episodes", "Reward", (-600, 300))

Building Actor Critic Network¶

The Actor-Critic network is a RL method that combines the actor and critic components into a single model. The actor component learns the policy that maps states to actions, while the critic component evaluates the quality of the actions taken by the actor and provides it with a error signal to guide improvement of the policy.

Init parameters and environment¶

In [ ]:
gamma = 0.99  # Discount factor for past rewards
max_steps_per_episode = 1000
max_episodes=2000
#init environment
env = gym.make('LunarLander-v2')
# set seeds
env.seed(21)
np.random.seed(21)
eps = np.finfo(np.float32).eps.item()  # Smallest number such that 1.0 + eps != 1.0

Build Model¶

In [ ]:
num_inputs = 8
num_actions = 4
num_hidden = 512

inputs = layers.Input(shape=(num_inputs,))
common1 = layers.Dense(num_hidden, activation="relu")(inputs)
common = layers.Dense(num_hidden, activation="relu")(common1)
action = layers.Dense(num_actions, activation="softmax")(common)
critic = layers.Dense(1)(common)

model = tf.keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=[action, critic])
model.summary()

Training¶

In [ ]:
optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001)
huber_loss = tf.keras.losses.Huber()
action_probs_history = []
critic_value_history = []
rewards_history = []
running_reward = 0
episode_count = 0

while episode_count<max_episodes:  # Run until exceed reward threshold or maximum episodes
    state = env.reset()
    episode_reward = 0
    with tf.GradientTape() as tape:
        for timestep in range(1, max_steps_per_episode):
          # env.render()
          state = tf.convert_to_tensor(state)
          state = tf.expand_dims(state, 0)
          # Predict action probabilities and estimatedfuture rewards from env state
          action_probs, critic_value = model(state)
          critic_value_history.append(critic_value[0, 0])

          # Sample from action distribution
          action = np.random.choice(num_actions, p=np.squeeze(action_probs))
          action_probs_history.append(tf.math.log(action_probs[0, action]))

          # Apply the sampled action
          state, reward, done, _ = env.step(action)
          rewards_history.append(reward)
          episode_reward += reward

          if done:
            break

        # Update running reward
        running_reward = 0.05 * episode_reward + (1 - 0.05) * running_reward

        # Calculate expected value from rewards
        # - At each timestep what was the total reward received after that timestep
        # - Rewards in the past are discounted by multiplying them with gamma
        # - These are the labels for our critic
        returns = []
        discounted_sum = 0
        for r in rewards_history[::-1]:
            discounted_sum = r + gamma * discounted_sum
            returns.insert(0, discounted_sum)

        # Normalize
        returns = np.array(returns)
        returns = (returns - np.mean(returns)) / (np.std(returns) + eps)
        returns = returns.tolist()

        # Calculating loss values to update our network
        history = zip(action_probs_history, critic_value_history, returns)
        actor_losses = []
        critic_losses = []
        for log_prob, value, ret in history:
            # At this point in history, the critic estimated that we would get a
            # total reward = `value` in the future. We took an action with log probability
            # of `log_prob` and ended up recieving a total reward = `ret`.
            # The actor must be updated so that it predicts an action that leads to
            # high rewards (compared to critic's estimate) with high probability
            diff = ret - value
            actor_losses.append(-log_prob * diff)  # actor loss

            # The critic must be updated so that it predicts a better estimate of
            # the future rewards.
            critic_losses.append(
                huber_loss(tf.expand_dims(value, 0), tf.expand_dims(ret, 0))
            )

        # Backpropagation
        loss_value = sum(actor_losses) + sum(critic_losses)
        grads = tape.gradient(loss_value, model.trainable_variables)
        optimizer.apply_gradients(zip(grads, model.trainable_variables))

        # Clear the loss and reward history
        action_probs_history.clear()
        critic_value_history.clear()
        rewards_history.clear()

    # Log details
    episode_count += 1
    print(f'Episode {episode_count}: {episode_reward}')
    if episode_count % 10 == 0:
        print(f"running reward: {running_reward:.2f} at episode {episode_count}")

    if running_reward > 0:  # Condition to consider a decent model
        print(f"Solved at episode {episode_count}!")
        break

Summary¶

In training: The model never converged even after 2000 episodes, its performance was also very inconsistent. Sometimes the reward would spike up to 200+ and then in the next episode it would be negative. Therefore we will try other algorithms instead

Deep SARSA (State-Action-Reward-State-Action)¶

SARSA is a model-free RL algorithm that learns by updating the Q-value for a current state-action pair based on the reward and the estimated Q-value for the next state-action pair. This helps the agent make decisions because it has a better idea of the long-term reward of each possible action in a given state.

  • Using keras-RL library so we can easily test out different Policies and see the effect on the SARSA architecture
  • Save the model with best mean reward at the end of training
In [ ]:
#!pip install keras-rl

Boltzmann Q Policy¶

Selects actions based on the Boltzmann distribution over Q-values. It has a good balance of exploration and exploitation because it selects actions with higher Q-values more often, but also considers actions with lower Q-values sometimes

In [ ]:
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Activation, Flatten
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam

from rl.agents import SARSAAgent
from rl.policy import BoltzmannQPolicy, GreedyQPolicy, BoltzmannGumbelQPolicy, MaxBoltzmannQPolicy

ENV_NAME = 'LunarLander-v2'
In [ ]:
# Get environment 
env = gym.make(ENV_NAME)
np.random.seed(21)
env.seed(21)
nb_actions = 4

# Build model
model = Sequential()
model.add(Flatten(input_shape=(1,) + env.observation_space.shape))
model.add(Dense(256))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(Dense(256))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(Dense(256))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(Dense(nb_actions))
model.add(Activation('linear'))
print(model.summary())

# Select policy
policy = BoltzmannQPolicy()
# policy = GreedyQPolicy()
# policy = BoltzmannGumbelQPolicy()
sarsa1 = SARSAAgent(model=model, nb_actions=nb_actions, nb_steps_warmup=10, gamma=0.99, policy=policy)
sarsa1.compile(Adam(lr=0.001), metrics=['mae'])
sarsa1.fit(env, nb_steps=70000, visualize=False, verbose=2)

Boltzmann Gumbel Q Policy¶

Similar to the BoltzmannQPolicy, but uses the Gumbel-Softmax distribution instead of the Boltzmann distribution, more suitable for backpropagation.

In [ ]:
# Get environment 
env = gym.make(ENV_NAME)
np.random.seed(21)
env.seed(21)
nb_actions = 4

# Build model
model = Sequential()
model.add(Flatten(input_shape=(1,) + env.observation_space.shape))
model.add(Dense(256))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(Dense(256))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(Dense(256))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(Dense(nb_actions))
model.add(Activation('linear'))
print(model.summary())

# Select policy
# policy = BoltzmannQPolicy()
# policy = GreedyQPolicy()
policy = BoltzmannGumbelQPolicy()
sarsa2 = SARSAAgent(model=model, nb_actions=nb_actions, nb_steps_warmup=10, gamma=0.99, policy=policy)
sarsa2.compile(Adam(lr=0.001), metrics=['mae'])
sarsa2.fit(env, nb_steps=70000, visualize=False, verbose=2)

Max Boltzmann Q Policy¶

Similar to the BoltzmannQPolicy, but instead of selecting actions based on the Boltzmann distribution, it selects the action with the highest probability after applying a softmax transformation to the Q-values

In [ ]:
# Get environment 
env = gym.make(ENV_NAME)
np.random.seed(21)
env.seed(21)
nb_actions = 4

# Build model
model = Sequential()
model.add(Flatten(input_shape=(1,) + env.observation_space.shape))
model.add(Dense(256))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(Dense(256))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(Dense(256))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(Dense(nb_actions))
model.add(Activation('linear'))
print(model.summary())

# Select policy
# policy = BoltzmannQPolicy()
# policy = GreedyQPolicy()
# policy = BoltzmannGumbelQPolicy()
policy = MaxBoltzmannQPolicy()
sarsa3 = SARSAAgent(model=model, nb_actions=nb_actions, nb_steps_warmup=10, gamma=0.99, policy=policy)
sarsa3.compile(Adam(lr=0.001), metrics=['mae'])
sarsa3.fit(env, nb_steps=70000, visualize=False, verbose=2)

Greedy Q Policy¶

This policy selects actions with the highest estimated Q-value. It only explores with probability 0, best for exploitation not so much for exploration

In [ ]:
# Get environment 
env = gym.make(ENV_NAME)
np.random.seed(21)
env.seed(21)
nb_actions = 4

# Build model
model = Sequential()
model.add(Flatten(input_shape=(1,) + env.observation_space.shape))
model.add(Dense(256))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(Dense(256))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(Dense(256))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(Dense(nb_actions))
model.add(Activation('linear'))
print(model.summary())

# Select policy
# policy = BoltzmannQPolicy()
policy = GreedyQPolicy()
# policy = BoltzmannGumbelQPolicy()
sarsa4 = SARSAAgent(model=model, nb_actions=nb_actions, nb_steps_warmup=10, gamma=0.99, policy=policy)
sarsa4.compile(Adam(lr=0.001), metrics=['mae'])
sarsa4.fit(env, nb_steps=70000, visualize=False, verbose=2)

Building Deep Q-Network¶

Deep Q Networks (DQN) are a type of Reinforcement Learning (RL) algorithm that uses a neural network to approximate the Q-function, which is used to determine the optimal action to take in a given state. Its a variant of Q-learning, and we will be using experience replay to stabilize learning to improve performance.

Parameters¶

  • Learning Rate: It determines the size of the update steps taken by the algorithm to adjust the weights of the neural network.
  • Gamma(): Also known as the discount factor, it determines the importance of future rewards compared to the present reward. The higher the value means that future rewards are considered more important. (0 < < 1)
  • Epsilon (): Epsilon determines the balance between exploration and exploitation in the DQN algorithm, meaning that the higher the epsilon, the more likely it is to explore randomly.
  • Epsilon Decay: It refers to the gradual reduction of the exploration rate over time. As th model becomes more confident, it becomes less necessary to explore and more important to exploit the learned knowledge. Thus, encouraging the agent to shift from a more exploratory to a more exploitative strategy.
In [16]:
class DQN:
    def __init__(self, env, lr, gamma, epsilon, epsilon_decay):
        self.env = env
        self.action_space = env.action_space
        self.observation_space = env.observation_space
        self.counter = 0

        self.lr = lr
        self.gamma = gamma
        self.epsilon = epsilon
        self.epsilon_decay = epsilon_decay
        self.rewards_list = []

        self.replay_memory_buffer = deque(maxlen=500000)
        self.batch_size = 64
        self.epsilon_min = 0.01
        self.num_action_space = self.action_space.n
        self.num_observation_space = env.observation_space.shape[0]
        self.model = self.initialize_model()
        self.stats = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Episode', 'Step','x-coor', 'y-coor', 'x-velo', 'y-velo', 'angle', 'angular velocity', 'left-touch', 'right-touch'])

    def initialize_model(self):
        model = tf.keras.Sequential()
        model.add(layers.Dense(512, input_dim=self.num_observation_space, activation='relu'))
        model.add(layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'))
        model.add(layers.Dense(self.num_action_space, activation=tf.keras.activations.linear))

        # Compile the model
        model.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.mean_squared_error,optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(lr=self.lr))
        print(model.summary())
        return model

    def get_action(self, state):
        if np.random.rand() < self.epsilon:
            return random.randrange(self.num_action_space)

        predicted_actions = self.model.predict(state)
        return np.argmax(predicted_actions[0])

    def add_to_replay_memory(self, state, action, reward, next_state, done):
        self.replay_memory_buffer.append((state, action, reward, next_state, done))

    def learn_and_update_weights_by_reply(self):
        # replay_memory_buffer size check
        if len(self.replay_memory_buffer) < self.batch_size or self.counter != 0:
            return

        # Early Stopping
        if np.mean(self.rewards_list[-10:]) > 180: #if average reward in last 10 episodes >180
            return

        random_sample = self.get_random_sample_from_replay_mem()
        states, actions, rewards, next_states, done_list = self.get_attributes_from_sample(random_sample)
        targets = rewards + self.gamma * (np.amax(self.model.predict_on_batch(next_states), axis=1)) * (1 - done_list)
        target_vec = self.model.predict_on_batch(states)
        indexes = np.array([i for i in range(self.batch_size)])
        target_vec[[indexes], [actions]] = targets

        self.model.fit(states, target_vec, epochs=1, verbose=0)

    def get_attributes_from_sample(self, random_sample):
        states = np.array([i[0] for i in random_sample])
        actions = np.array([i[1] for i in random_sample])
        rewards = np.array([i[2] for i in random_sample])
        next_states = np.array([i[3] for i in random_sample])
        done_list = np.array([i[4] for i in random_sample])
        states = np.squeeze(states)
        next_states = np.squeeze(next_states)
        return np.squeeze(states), actions, rewards, next_states, done_list

    def get_random_sample_from_replay_mem(self):
        random_sample = random.sample(self.replay_memory_buffer, self.batch_size)
        return random_sample

    def train(self, num_episodes=2000, can_stop=True,render=True):
        
        for episode in range(num_episodes):
            state = env.reset()
            reward_for_episode = 0
            num_steps = 1000
            state = np.reshape(state, [1, self.num_observation_space])
            for step in range(num_steps):
                # Recording the state every 100 steps
                if step % 100 == 0:
                    curr_stat = np.array([episode,step])
                    curr_stat = np.append(curr_stat,state)
                    self.stats.loc[len(self.stats)] = curr_stat
                if render:
                  env.render()
                received_action = self.get_action(state)
                # print("received_action:", received_action)
                next_state, reward, done, info = env.step(received_action)
                next_state = np.reshape(next_state, [1, self.num_observation_space])
                # Store the experience in replay memory
                self.add_to_replay_memory(state, received_action, reward, next_state, done)
                # add up rewards
                reward_for_episode += reward
                state = next_state
                self.update_counter()
                self.learn_and_update_weights_by_reply()

                if done:
                    break
            self.rewards_list.append(reward_for_episode)

            # Decay the epsilon after each experience completion
            if self.epsilon > self.epsilon_min:
                self.epsilon *= self.epsilon_decay

            # Check for breaking condition
            last_rewards_mean = np.mean(self.rewards_list[-100:])
            if last_rewards_mean > 200 and can_stop:
                print("DQN Training Complete...")
                break
            print(episode, "\t: Episode || Reward: ",reward_for_episode, "\t|| Average Reward: ",last_rewards_mean, "\t epsilon: ", self.epsilon)

    def update_counter(self):
        self.counter += 1
        step_size = 5
        self.counter = self.counter % step_size

    def save(self, name):
        self.model.save(name)

#TRAINING

Best Parameters¶

  • 0.9 epsilon decay: 266 avg reward
  • 0.001 learning rate: 245 avg reward
  • 0.99 gamma: 251 avg reward
  • Now using these parameters we will retrain the model without stopping it so we can get the most learning output
In [ ]:
#init environment
env = gym.make('LunarLander-v2')

# set seeds
env.seed(21)
np.random.seed(21)
# setting up hypertuned params
lr = 0.001
epsilon = 1.0
epsilon_decay = 0.9
gamma = 0.99
training_episodes = 2000
model = DQN(env, lr, gamma, epsilon, epsilon_decay)
model.train(training_episodes,  can_stop=False)

save_dir = "0-COLLAB"
# Save trained model
model.save(save_dir + "/savedModels/tuned_model.h5")

# Save Rewards list
pickle.dump(model.rewards_list, open(save_dir + "/train_rewards_list.p", "wb"))
rewards_list = pickle.load(open(save_dir + "/train_rewards_list.p", "rb"))
# plot reward in graph
reward_df = pd.DataFrame(rewards_list)
plot_df(reward_df, "Figure 1: Reward for each training episode", "Reward for each training episode", "Episode","Reward")
print("Training Complete")

Plot angle of ship over time during training¶

We can see that there are much more spikes at the beginning of training, indicating that the ship was angled more sharply at the beginning as the model did not know what it was doing, it would just rotate 90 degrees and fly to the ground and crash. Overtime the general trend is the angle decreasing as the model learns to fly the ship with more stability.

plt.title('Angle of ship during training')
plt.show()

Similar to earlier, there are much less spikes in velocity when training goes on. This makes sense because the ship must maintain a relatively low velocity to land safely. In the region of ~400-600 episodes, we can see there is a trough in avg x-velocity. This could mean that the ship is barely moving away from the original position horizontally, this can be bad because the ship usually must move some amount to get into the landing pad area.

Conclusion¶

A great result from our final model which consistently lands the ship in the landing area with high consistency, and lands the ship in general with even higher consistency. We learned how to implement different RL Architectures/Algorithms as well as how to tune them properly.
